nd":"Brewood, Staffordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, England"},"en":{"1463–1494":"1463–1494","1465–1520":"1465–1520","1487–Male":"1487–Deceased","1494–1544":"1494–1544","1495–1528":"1495–1528","–Female":"Deceased","1425–1471":"1425–1471","1437–1470":"1437–1470","1451":"1451","1495":"1495","1494":"1494","1471":"1471","1470":"1470","1437":"1437","1425":"1425","1544":"1544","1487":"1487","1520":"1520","1465":"1465","1463":"1463","about 1486":"about 1486","about 1487":"about 1487","1528":"1528","about 1494":"about 1494","Brewood, Staffordshire, England":"Brewood, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","Brewood, Staffordshire, Kingdom of England":"Brewood, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Fowke","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English: relationship name from the Middle English, Anglo-Norman French personal name  <i>Folk</i>,  <i>Fulk</i>,  <i>Fuke</i>.  Compare  Foxon  . For a variant form of the personal name  see  Foulkes  .  See also  Fudge  , which may sometimes be a variant form."],"variants":[{"name":"Fudge","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from the Middle English, Anglo-Norman French personal name <i>Fulch</i> or <i>Fuche</i>, usually a pet form of Old French <i>Fulcher</i>, <i>Fucher</i> (see   Fulcher  ). Voicing of ‘ch’ to soft ‘g’ gave rise to <i>Fudge</i>. The name may sometimes have been interchangeable with <b>Fowke</b> (for which see   Foulk   1), derived from a pet form of this and other Old French personal names in <i>Fulc-</i>.","English: habitational name from Fuge, in Blackawton, Devon. This placename is composed of Old English <i>feoh</i> ‘cattle’ + <i>wīc</i> ‘farm, dairy farm, village’."]},{"name":"Folke","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Fowke  ."]},{"name":"Fook","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Fowke  ."]},{"name":"Foulk","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from the Middle English and Anglo-Norman French personal name <i>Fulk</i>, which is of ancient Germanic origin, ultimately from an element meaning ‘folk, people’."]},{"name":"Fogg","meanings":["English (northern): possibly a variant of <b>Fowke</b> (see   Foulk   1). It may derive from Middle English <i>fogge</i> ‘aftermath’ (i.e. grass left to grow after the hay has been cut, also applied to long grass in a water meadow), especially in northern England, where the term occurs as a specifying element in minor placenames, but as it is not found on its own as a simplex name, the derivation is doubtful without some supporting evidence. The word <i>fogge</i>, which is probably of Old Norse origin, is still in use as a dialect term in Craven, Yorkshire, and in eastern Lancashire. modern English <i>fog</i> ‘thick mist’ is first attested in the 16th century and is unlikely to be the source of the surname."]},{"name":"Fuke","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Fowke   and  compare  Fook  ."]},{"name":"Folk","meanings":["German: variant of   Volk   1 and, in North America, also an altered form of this. This form of the surname is also found in Czechia.","English: variant of   Foulk   1."]},{"name":"Focke","meanings":["North German, East Frisian, and Dutch: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Folco</i>, a pet form of various names beginning with <i>Folc-</i> or <i>Volk-</i>; cognate with   Foulk   1.","English (of Norman origin): variant of   Foulk   1. See also   Foulks  ."]},{"name":"Foulke","meanings":["English (Derbyshire and Shropshire): variant of   Foulk  ."]},{"name":"Fulk","meanings":["English: variant of   Foulk   1.","Altered form of German   Volk   or   Falk  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Fowke was born in 1463, in Brewood, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Roger Fowke, was 38 and his mother, Elizabeth Wybaston, was 26. He married Jane Streethay about 1486, in Brewood, Staffordshire, England. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 1 daughter. He died in 1494, in his hometown, at the age of 31."},"et":{"1463–1494":"1463–1494","1465–1520":"1465–1520","1487–Male":"1487–Surnud","1494–1544":"1494–1544","1495–1528":"1495–1528","–Female":"Surnud","1425–1471":"1425–1471","1437–1470":"1437–1470","1451":"1451","1495":"1495","1494":"1494","1471":"1471","1470":"1470","1437":"1437","1425":"1425","1544":"1544","1487":"1487","1520":"1520","1465":"1465","1463":"1463","about 1486":"umbes 1486","about 1487":"umbes 1487","1528":"1528","about 1494":"umbes 1494","Brewood, Staffordshire, England":"Brewood, Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Brewood, Staffordshire, Kingdom of England":"Brewood, Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, England"},"fi":{"1463–1494":"1463–1494","1465–1520":"1465–1520","1487–Male":"1487–Kuollut","1494–1544":"1494–1544","1495–1528":"1495–1528","–Female":"Kuollut","1425–1471":"1425–1471","1437–1470":"1437–1470","1451":"1451","1495":"1495","1494":"1494","1471":"1471","1470":"1470","1437":"1437","1425":"1425","1544":"1544","1487":"1487","1520":"1520","1465":"1465","1463":"1463","about 1486":"noin 1486","about 1487":"